[
    {
        "content": "<p>In current roc, it's common to have a pipeline where the final stage is applying a tag. For example:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">pipe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">thing</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">doSomething</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Wrapper</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>In the dot-syntax world, this could be replicated with <code>pass_to</code>, maintaining the nice unidirectionality.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">pass_to_style</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">thing</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">do_something</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">pass_to</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Wrapper</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But would it make sense to allow tag application to look like a method call?:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">method_style</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">thing</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">do_something</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"kt\">Wrapper</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>So, a thread to discuss trade-offs, practicality, and offer opinions.</p>",
        "id": 487333782,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Nuttall",
        "timestamp": 1733861817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>my immediate reaction is that it looks strange to me, but I could also find myself getting used to it and liking it because it makes a common case more concise without making it less clear</p>",
        "id": 487337076,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1733863149
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One thing that occurred to me is that it might be strange to pass extra payloads that way. Presumably <code>\"one\".Wrapper(\"two\")</code> would be the same as <code>Wrapper \"one\" \"two\"</code>. </p>\n<p>Maybe method style tag application should be restricted to <code>.Wrapper()</code>?</p>\n<p><code>pass_to</code> could still handle multiple payloads via a lambda: <code>something.pass_to(\\x -&gt; Wrapper \"first\" x)</code></p>",
        "id": 487338607,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Nuttall",
        "timestamp": 1733863807
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I could see arguments either way on that</p>",
        "id": 487339631,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1733864046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not a new issue really, <code>\"first\" |&gt; Wrapper \"second\"</code> is already possible, and not really a problem I guess</p>",
        "id": 487339952,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Nuttall",
        "timestamp": 1733864182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I believe with the current proposal, wrapping multiple values would be this:<br>\n<code>\"one\".pass_to(Wrapper, \"two\")</code> to get <code>Wrapper \"one\" \"two\"</code></p>",
        "id": 487342644,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733865496
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd personally be pretty against that code. Just assigning an intermediate variable is much clearer.<br>\nI think piping works normally because you are \"acting upon\" the piped value. <br>\nIn this case it just looks weird to have two args.</p>\n<p>It's the kind of thing I would do at the time thinking I'm being clever, and then also call out in other people's PRs <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 487998480,
        "sender_full_name": "Eli Dowling",
        "timestamp": 1733882009
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To be fair, I don't think I have ever pipe to a tag that took more than one arg</p>",
        "id": 488002066,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733884342
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So yeah, I would probably add an intermediate variable</p>",
        "id": 488002077,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733884353
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I do because it's convenient, and then get unhappy when I see the code again</p>",
        "id": 488002092,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1733884366
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just see no reason to deny that if it works with local functions</p>",
        "id": 488002094,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733884368
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So it's probably better to incentivize tags in the front</p>",
        "id": 488002115,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1733884388
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hmm....</p>",
        "id": 488002377,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733884596
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>fair enough</p>",
        "id": 488002390,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1733884605
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Putting a tag (especially <code>Ok</code>) at the start of an expression often feels like introducing noise to me. I find it's nice to put the Ok off to the right so the content is emphasised, rather than the wrapper.</p>\n<p>I wrote this for an advent of code solution, and chose to pipe to Ok, even though the expression to the left reads RTL.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">when</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">char</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">is</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Close</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'&lt;'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Angle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'&gt;'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Close</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Angle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Round</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Close</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Round</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Curly</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"p\">}</span><span class=\"nf\">'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Close</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Curly</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">other</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Err</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">InvalidChar</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">other</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Potential other ways to write this with dot/brackets syntax:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">prefix</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">only</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">mixed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">direction</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">with</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">method</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">style</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">pass_to</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">method</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">only</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">keep</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">the</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">pipe</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Square</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Out of those, I prefer the 'keep the pipe' option. I don't think it looks good in multi-line dot chains though.</p>",
        "id": 488070625,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Nuttall",
        "timestamp": 1733915131
    }
]